          "title": "From Subsistence to Surplus: The Long View",
          "content": "Throughout much of human history, the economy saw very little growth. Even as the population increased, the amount of goods and services produced by each person remained almost unchanged from the time of the Roman Empire all the way to the Industrial Revolution. Greg Ip, an expert in economics, explains that this stagnation wasn't because people were lazy or incapable. Instead, it was largely due to the lack of one essential element: continuous technological innovation.\nBefore the Industrial Revolution, the only way economies could grow was by increasing the number of workers—thanks to population growth—or by adding more capital, such as clearing additional farmland or creating more tools. However, these methods had a limitation known as diminishing returns. This means that as you added more workers or equipment, the extra output produced became smaller and smaller. For example, if you farm too much land, the next piece of land you cultivate might not yield as much produce because it is less fertile. Similarly, if you hire too many workers, they might end up getting in each other's way, which can reduce overall productivity.\nThe real turning point came when a combination of the scientific method, widespread education, and property rights created an environment that encouraged and rewarded innovation. This was a significant change because it allowed new ideas and inventions to flourish. Innovations like the steam engine, the spinning jenny, and the power loom were not just simple tools; they acted as force multipliers. This means that they enabled each worker to produce significantly more than they could without these advancements.\nAs a result of these innovations, for the first time in history, the amount of goods and services produced per person began to rise consistently. This marked the start of a new era of sustained economic growth, a trend that continues today, although it can be uneven across different regions and populations. The journey from a stagnant economy to one of growth illustrates the importance of innovation and how it can transform societies, leading to improved living standards and opportunities for everyone. Understanding this evolution helps us appreciate the role of technology and creativity in shaping our world today.\nContext recap: Throughout much of human history, the economy saw very little growth. Even as the population increased, the amount of goods and services produced by each person remained almost unchanged from the time of the Roman Empire all the way to the Industrial Revolution. Greg Ip, an expert in economics, explains that this stagnation wasn't because people were lazy or incapable. Instead, it was largely due to the lack of one essential element: continuous technological innovation.\nWhy this matters: From Subsistence to Surplus: The Long View helps learners in Economics connect ideas from The Little Book of Economics: How the Economy Works in the Real World to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
